{"tid":146814,"cid":5,"subCid":0,"title":"（女權撚）成功爭取紅綠燈公仔有著裙","createTime":"2017-03-07T11:44:32.000Z","updateTime":"2017-03-08T05:59:29.000Z","uid":77164,"like":2,"dislike":131,"uniUserReply":0,"replies":[{"pid":"e6230449a5e386cc1f88cc1df28ea513027bd91a","tid":146814,"uid":77164,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-03-07T11:44:32.000Z","msg":"<img src=\"https://img.eservice-hk.net/upload/2017/03/07/194245_be40ffabc067a52a4f72ba273074f432.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fimg.eservice-hk.net%2Fupload%2F2017%2F03%2F07%2F194245_be40ffabc067a52a4f72ba273074f432.jpg&h=d2d5284d&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n<br />\nALL of Victoria&rsquo;s pedestrian crossings could eventually have an equal number of female and male walking signals in a push for gender equality.<br />\n<br />\nBut critics say the plan is political correctness gone mad.<br />\n<br />\nInfluential lobby group the Committee for Melbourne says having green or red silhouettes only of men at traffic lights reinforces unconscious bias by discriminating against women.<br />\n<br />\nThe Equal Crossings initiative is kicking off its campaign this week with 10 female &shy;pedestrian figures to be installed at the intersection of Swanston and Flinders streets.<br />\n<br />\nThe VicRoads-approved trial will run for 12 months but organisers will seek changes to the Road Safety Act to achieve 1:1 male and female representation at crossings across the state in the long term.<br />\n<br />\nVicRoads director of metropolitan projects central Brendan Pauwels said he was partly swayed by his eight-year-old daughter who questioned &ldquo;why all the crossing symbols were men&rdquo;.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;To me that&rsquo;s good enough reason to support it,&rdquo; he said.<br />\n<br />\nMore than 5400 people have voted on a <a href=\"http://heraldsun.com.au\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=http%3A%2F%2Fheraldsun.com.au&d=cw67THcQ8%2BNa%2BfcBlgGHU%2F755KD0hvcRsprRlRVhNBc%3D&h=149dbf39\" data-auto-link target=\"_blank\">heraldsun.com.au</a> poll asking whether Victoria&rsquo;s pedestrian crossings should have an equal number of female and male walking signals.<br />\n<br />\n94 per cent of respondents have voted &lsquo;No&rsquo;.<br />\n<br />\nWhile more than 400 readers have commented on this morning&rsquo;s report, many opposing the idea.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;How absolutely ridiculous, especially as most girls/women wear pants as in jeans etc,&rdquo; writes Jenny.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;What a total waste of money.&rdquo;<br />\n<br />\nWhile Gary posted: &ldquo;This is easy fixed. Why not have both symbols on &lsquo;all&rsquo; crossing lights so that women will know they can cross the road too.&rdquo;<br />\n<br />\nThe report has also drawn strong reaction on Facebook, with 3000 comments posted overnight.<br />\n<br />\nSCROLL DOWN TO JOIN THE DEBATE OR HEAD TO OUR FACEBOOK PAGE<br />\n<br />\nThis morning, Equality Minister Martin Foley said it was important to have women equally represented across society.<br />\n<br />\nHe said he had not thought about the traffic light symbols before but that &ldquo;it doesn&rsquo;t mean it&rsquo;s not an important issue&rdquo;.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;Maybe there is such a thing as unconscious bias, maybe the symbols that we present to our kids and to others really do have an impact on us,&rdquo; Mr Foley said.<br />\n<br />\n以後個啲馬路女人行曬<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/hoho.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/hoho.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/hoho.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <br />\n見到個三條女個西樣真係作嘔<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/fuck.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/fuck.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"9673c544af1a9e67a6f199ed01ef3f7a99e006b6","tid":146814,"uid":57462,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-03-07T11:45:14.000Z","msg":"無撚聊，唔幫佢著埋件衫？"},{"pid":"81b3cbef11579a939f747d3639815a8a